{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4e25ca5d-c8cd-4691-a03e-676313be0bf7","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a `dotnet tool`:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a .NET tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `OutputType` must be `Exe` | Tools must be console apps |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server            # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the critical additions beyond normal NuGet package metadata.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3193d95b-98f7-4a1a-ab38-ba5eb649d4d3","outputTokens":474,"requestId":"3845:2A9B4:6FE7B8E:784DAC3:6A03D099"},"id":"e9b138ee-1a1f-4cd9-8754-c2cff3962b6a","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:15:15.025Z","parentId":"20278c59-a219-4e37-968c-76fff6eef780"}
